{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501739"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:33:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:33:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1784"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1784"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.1,0.05,0.27,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1784"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81884"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1784"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1784"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67161"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"920"},{"type":"tags","id":"2136"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1182"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1244"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81884"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with right groin pain after an unwitnessed fall at home. He usually mobilises with a walking stick but had forgotten to use it at the time. He has a medical history of Parkinson\u0027s disease, postural hypotension, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His medications include levodopa-carbidopa and metformin. He is a non-smoker. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has tenderness over the right groin. A pelvic X-ray shows no obvious fractures. A CT scan reveals an undisplaced fracture of the right inferior pubic ramus. His pain is well-controlled with oral analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mobilise as tolerated","Bed rest for one week","Traction for one week","Pelvic binder","Surgical fixation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an undisplaced inferior pubic ramus fracture, which is a stable pelvic injury classified as a fragility fracture of the pelvic ring (FFP) type Ia. The key principles of management are adequate analgesia and early mobilisation to prevent complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMobilise as tolerated\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Early mobilisation prevents complications such as deep vein thrombosis, muscle deconditioning, and pressure injuries. Since this patient\u0027s pain is well-controlled with analgesia and the fracture is stable, he should be encouraged to weight-bear as tolerated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBed rest\u003C/strong\u003E for one week is inappropriate as prolonged immobilisation increases the risk of complications including deep vein thrombosis, pressure injuries, and deconditioning. This is particularly important in elderly patients who can rapidly lose muscle strength and function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETraction\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for stable, undisplaced fractures. It would be overly restrictive and potentially harmful in this case. Traction may be considered for certain displaced pelvic fractures as a temporary measure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic binder\u003C/strong\u003E application is reserved for patients with unstable pelvic fractures or those at risk of significant haemorrhage. This patient has a stable fracture pattern without evidence of haemodynamic compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical fixation\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for unstable, displaced, or open fractures, or when there are associated injuries requiring operative intervention. This patient\u0027s fracture is stable and undisplaced, making conservative management appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Undisplaced pubic ramus fractures can be safely managed with early mobilisation and adequate analgesia.","Prolonged bed rest increases risk of complications including deep vein thrombosis and pressure injuries.","Surgical fixation and pelvic binders are reserved for unstable or displaced pelvic fractures."],"references":["Rommens PM, Hofmann A. Comprehensive classification of fragility fractures of the pelvic ring: Recommendations for surgical treatment [Internet]. Injury. Elsevier Ltd; 2013 [cited 2021Jan22]. Available from: https://www.injuryjournal.com/article/S0020-1383(13)00304-5/abstract","Cook E, Laycock J, Sivapathasuntharam D, et al. Surgical versus non-surgical management of lateral compression type-1 pelvic fracture in adults 60 years and older: the L1FE RCT. Health Technol Assess. 2024;28(15):1-67. doi:10.3310/LAPW3412"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67161"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1784"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67161"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T11:31:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T11:33:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1784"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","